Bringing War Home: Violent Crime, Police Killings and the Overmilitarization of the US Police
∗
Federico Masera
September 13, 2016
Abstract
The withdrawal from the Afghan and Iraqi war led to the arrival of huge quantities of military equipment to the US. Many of these now unused military equipment have been redistributed to police departments via a program called 1033. In this paper I study the causal e ect on criminal activity and police behavior of the militarization of the police through this program. I do so by taking into account that unused military equipment are stored in various disposition centers and police departments must cover all transportation costs but do not pay for the cost of item. I then use the closeness to a disposition center and the timing of the US withdrawal from the wars in a instrumental variable setting. Estimates show that military equipment reduces violent crime in part by displacing it to neighboring areas with less military equipment. Because of the decentralized nature of this program displacement e ects lead to an overmilitarization of the police. Estimates suggest the militarization of the police is a major factor in the recent reduction of violent crime and is responsible for 60% of the rapid drop in violent crime observed since 2007, preventing a total of 1.8 million violent crimes. Finally, I show that police militarization increases police killings and that all of the recent increase is due to program 1033. In total police militarization has killed 2200 people.
