1 Introduction
Each day more than 200 operations using military equipment and tactics are deployed by the police in the US [Kraska (2007); Coyne and Hall-blanco (2016)]. Conservatives estimates show that almost 70% of the US population lives under the jurisdiction of local enforcement agencies with military weapons. In very few years over 1 billion dollars in military equipment have been distributed to policemen across the US 1. This phenomenon, that is changing how one of the most basic public goods is provided, is not con ned to the US. As terrorist threats have escalated in the last years many police forces in Europe have started using military-grade equipment. In the developing world police departments have been heavily militarized since many years and in some cases the army is directly used in order to  ght crime2. Although the use of military equipment by police has become widespread around the world very little is know on its e ects. In the US, police departments, sheri  o ces and pro-police movements, defend the militarization of the police as a needed tool for e ective and safe law enforcement. On the other side of the debate, civil liberties and activist groups, see the overmilitarization of the police as violation of constitutional rights and fear that it will increase police brutality.
In this paper I provide causal inference on the e ects that the militarization of the police has on criminal activity and police behavior. I do so by studying  program 1033 , the main program that transfers military equipment to police departments in the US. As the army started withdrawing from the Afghan and Iraqi wars military equipment returned to the US and was then distributed to police departments through this program. For estimating the causal e ect of military equipment I use the fact that, when returning from war, military
