I  rst show that the militarization of the police is able to reduce violent crimes. For each dollar per capita of military equipment possessed by a police department violent crime is reduced by 7 percent. At least one third of the e ect is due to displacing criminal activity to neighboring areas. These estimates predict that program 1033 has prevented almost 1.8 million violent crimes. Conservative cost estimates imply 78 billion US dollar in prevented costs to the victims of these violent crimes and the US justice system. Additionally, these estimates show how the militarization of the police is an important factor of the acceleration of the secular drop in violent crime in the US. Since 2007 violent crimes have decreased an impressive 18%. Estimates suggest that more than 60% of this drop is due to the militarization of the police. Finally, the displacement of criminals due to program 1033 has important implications for the optimality of the decision of militarization of each police department. As police departments don't have to take into account the negatives externalities on neighboring police departments, in equilibrium police departments are overmilitarized.
I then focus my analysis on one of the most discussed outcomes related to police mili-
