This paper is  rst of all related to works that investigate the causes and e ects of the militarization of the police. Balko (2014) provides a complete analysis of the history of police militarization and a description of the policies and practices that led to a level of militarization unprecedented in the history of the US. ACLU (2014) reports the results of sending to 260 enforcement agencies public records request. The study shows how enforcement agencies have become highly militarized due to the use of federal program like 1033 and the main use of military equipment is in drug raids. Closer my paper, Bove and Gavrilova (2015) investigate the e ects of program 1033 on crime and conclude that the militarization of the police reduces street crime level. I improve on this study by using a more detailed data on the militarization of the police that let me study displacement e ects and ultimately show the existence of an overmilitarization in the US. Secondly, with this new data I can focus my attention on local enforcement agencies instead of the full set enforcement forces in the US. The main advantage is that local enforcement agencies have non-overlapping jurisdictions. Because of this any increase in militarization in one jurisdiction shouldn't have any e ect on other jurisdiction unless that criminals decide to move. Finally, with this new dataset I do not incur in the problem of having overrepresentation of the policing resources of the county that includes the capital of the state. This problem arises because most of the state and federal agencies are normally located in the capital but their jurisdiction is more broad than a county. Additionally, I study the e ects of militarization of some new outcome, police killings. This phenomenon has lately enters the public discussion in relation with the militarization of the police and is an important dimension to take into account when evaluating the overall impact of program 1033. More importantly, I also improve on the identi cation
