More broadly my paper is related to the literature that studies the e ects of policing on crime. Most recent literature review can be found in Chal n, Mccrary and Berkeley (2015). Most related to my analysis are studies that exploit quasi-experiments to try to uncover the elasticities of crime to changes in policing. The main worry in this literature, as in my paper, is the endogeneity of policing. The main concern here is that police departments that expect increases in crime boost their policing e orts and this confounds any potential negative e ects of policing on crime. The  rst paper trying to deal with this problem is Levitt (1997) that uses the timing of mayoral and gubernatorial elections as an instrument from changes in policing. Of special relevance to my study are the papers by Di Tella and Schargrodsky (2004) and Draca, Machin and Witt (2011) that use terrorist attacks in Buenos Aires and London and the subsequent deployment of police in some speci c areas of these cities as an exogenous shock to policing to study the e ects on crime. Other papers like Machin and Marie (2011) and Evans and Owens (2007) instead use the allocation of additional resources in some cities of UK and the US to study the e ectiveness of policing
