on crime reduction. This literature shows that an increase in policing is generally e ective at reducing crime. My main contribution to this literature is the study of a speci c change in policing: the use of military weapons by the police. Furthermore, I'm also the  rst to provide causal evidence on the determinants of police killings. Additionally, in my study I uncover some geographical displacement e ects that are in line with the classical theories of rational criminals but previously received very little empirical evidence. Instead of using a case study of one or a few cities as previously done by some of the papers in the literature I investigate the average e ect over all the US. Given that the sample used in this paper includes the universe of local enforcement agencies in the US there are no particular worries for the external validity of my results. The high amounts of police departments allows me to study the heterogeneity of the e ects of policing on crime. Finally is important to notice that my estimates are identi ed from a completely new source of variation. In particular the cross-sectional variation I exploit is a combination of the position of military bases in the US, that were mostly built during the WW2, and the selection of storage facilities, that were selected in 1997. Di erently from the others papers in the literature what I exploit is an event that happened many years before the activation of the treatment (in my paper is the arrival of military weapons for the wars) to identify the e ect. I later shown in the paper how this new methodology may plausibly identify the causal e ect of militarization of the police.
The structure of the paper is as follows: In section 2 I will present the data that is used with particular attention to how program 1033 works. Section 3 I presents the econometric strategy, the main results and discuss the validity of the identifying assumption. In Section 4 I explore the potential mechanisms that could create these results. Section 5 studies the e ect of militarization on police safety and police killings. Finally, in section 6, I conclude.
